<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel checks of the value added tax administration between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The material presented reports on the progress and results of the parallel controls carried out by the Supreme audit office, Czech republic and Najvyšším kontrolným úradom of the Slovak republic, which were aimed at the area of the administration of value added tax and the use of information system VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System – a System for the exchange of information on value added tax).</seg>
<seg id="4">In may 2004, joined the Czech republic and the Slovak republic to the European union, revenue from value added tax, therefore, not only affect the state budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel control actions were mainly focused on the control procedure of tax administrators in examining the amount of value added tax paid on the commercial transactions effected between the member states of the European union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of the VIES allow the electronic exchange of information on the registration of payers of value added tax in the individual member states of the European union and of the commercial transactions carried out by these payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">A mismatch between the data in the VIES and data in the tax return for value added tax submitted by the payer should the tax administrator to draw attention to suspected cases and to allow detection of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The contribution made parallel controls consisted not only in the exchange of information on the procedure of the financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but in particular in the examination of the use of VIES in monitoring the application of the right to exemption from value added tax on the intrakomunitárních transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The knowledge gained in the implementation of parallel checks are beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of other parallel controls in cooperation with the audit institutions of the member states of the European union.</seg>
