<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the administration of Value Added Tax and excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">This informational material provides an overview of the progress and results of the parallel control actions performed by the Supreme audit office and the Najvyšším kontrolným úradom S-skej of the republic, which were aimed at the area of the administration of the value-added and excise taxes.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the supreme audit offices of the two countries was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement in the control activities concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The theme of parallel control actions were selected with regard to the fact that indirect taxes are a significant contributor to the income of the state budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The design of the value added tax, allowing the return of the excess deduction, provides room for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High excise tax rates, in particular for tobacco and tobacco products, ethyl alcohol and mineral oils, they mean a high profit for those who escape from taxation of the illegal sale of these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Due to the need to address this issue comprehensively in the context of the whole of the European union the supreme audit institutions of the member countries of the European union created a working group of the VAT Working Group, to whose activities they are actively involved and miti-er control authorities of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="10">The biggest benefit of control actions can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but in particular in a joint effort to identify the problem areas of the administration of indirect taxes with the aim of reducing the space for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">Obtained experience and knowledge will be utilized in the framework of planned inspections of indirect taxes, focusing primarily on the involvement of administrators of the taxes of the two states to the system VIES, allowing to control the movement of goods between member states of the European union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the control of Value Added Tax Administration and excise duties for the years 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Control number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value Added Tax and excise duty</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) control of the procedure of the tax administrator for the administration, control and enforcement of Value Added Tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="18">11.2. 2004 was signed the Agreement on cooperation in supervisory activities between the Supreme audit office (hereinafter "SAO") and Najvyšším kontrolným úradom of the Slovak republic (hereinafter referred to as "SAO SR"). The subject of the contract was the cooperation when conducted parallel control events "value added Tax and excise taxes", included in the audit plan of the SAO for the year 2004 under no. 04/07 and "Control procedure of the administrators of dane pri administration, control and vymáhaní dan z pridanej values and spotrebních taxes", included in the audit plan of the SAO SR under no. 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">Cooperation consisted in the exchange of information to the extent provided for in the concluded treaty and in the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties in the treaty have undertaken to each other to provide information from public sources, from the database of the customs administration and from the files of the tax bodies conducted by the financial authorities in the Czech republic and tax authorities in the Slovak republic, which the contracting parties could not obtain in monitoring the application of value added tax and excise taxes on imports and exports from sources on the territory of the competent state.</seg>
<seg id="21">Checks were carried out in parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech republic (hereinafter "CR") the audit was carried out by the department of the state budget and territorial unions of south Bohemia, northeast Bohemia, south Moravia, central Moravia and north Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">Controlled persons were the General directorate of customs and 12 selected financial authorities: Financial office for Prague 1, the Financial office for Prague 3, Financial office in České Budějovice, the Financial office in Frýdek-Místek, the Financial office in Hodonín, the tax office in Jihlava, the Financial office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, the Financial office in Kroměříž, the irs in the Sand, the Financial office in the city of rožnově pod Radhoštěm, the Financial office in Ústí nad Orlicí, Financial office in velké Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">Control on the territory of the Slovak republic (hereinafter "SR") was carried out Sections of the tax and customs administration, the SAO SR, in cooperation with the Expoziturami the SAO SR in Banská Bystrica and Kosice on 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Daňový úrad Bratislava pre selected tax entities, the Tax office Bratislava III, the Tax office in Trnava, the Tax office Pooh-breeding, the Tax office Banská Bystrica Also, the Tax office Liptovský Mikuláš, the Tax office Žilina Also, the Tax office Žilina II, the Tax office Košice I and the Tax office Košice IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of control</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the control actions was to examine the performance of obligations of financial or tax offices and customs offices in the administration of value added tax and excise taxes, focusing on the selection of these taxes on imports and exports of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of international cooperation was the verification of imports and exports of selected commodities between the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA in the customs database of the CZECH republic and the customs database of SR and their subsequent verification in the tax returns for the relevant financial or tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="29">The period under review was 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recap of control results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">In the framework of international cooperation, the SAO handed over the SAO SR from the customs database of the CZECH republic 22 206 items of the uniform customs declaration (hereinafter referred to as "JCD") on the imports and exports of goods between the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA and on the contrary, the SAO SR handed over the SAO from the customs database SR 30 of 221 items JCD.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison was made between source-targeting items JCD from tariff database of the CZECH republic and the customs database SR.</seg>
<seg id="34">Of the 5,883 selected JCD items from the Czech Customs database, a total of 43% of related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Of the 12,343 selected JCD items from the SR Customs database, a total of 26% of related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="36">On the basis of the undistributed items JCD was on the financial or tax authorities carried out a selection of writings tax entities, which have been declared by the imports and exports subject to further verification, in cooperation with the customs administrations of the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA.</seg>
<seg id="37">On the basis of the exchange of information from the supporting documents to the customs administrations of the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA and the financial or tax authorities was on the territory of the second state of the verified implementation reported imports and exports between the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO SR carried out a joint pilot control at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma, in which both parties closely cooperate in the verification of the correctness of the data on the movement of goods between the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA.</seg>
<seg id="39">The inspection found deficiencies in the records of selected cases of imports and exports of goods realized in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation has allowed the examination of the business transactions between business partners from both states and pointed out the deficiencies in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="42">Check the SAO and the SAO SR in the field of international cooperation focused on the imports and exports of ethyl alcohol and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, or even other types of goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">On the basis of the writings of taxpayers to the selected financial, or tax offices, the SAO asked for verification of implementation of the exports of goods as reported on 40 JCD in the total statistical value 15 301 093 Czk and the SAO SR on the verification of the export, the statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and Sao SR have identified, inter alia, the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="45">- business transactions were on both sides declared the same way, which made it difficult the possibility of identifying appropriate imports and exports in the customs database of the CZECH republic and the customs database SR,</seg>
<seg id="46">- errors in the entry of data into customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports or exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- some exports from the Czech Republic have not been shown to produce adequate imports into the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="48">In these cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of unauthorized application of deductions for Value Added Tax,</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax entities did not comply with certain statutory obligations when reporting imports and exports in value added tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="50">- in the activities of the financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax and excise taxes and their interaction with the customs authorities, deficiencies were identified.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the field of value added tax and excise taxes will continue to need to pay attention to international trade in order to effectively minimize tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the activity of tax administrators in the exercise of value added tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="53">The basis of effective control of excise duties is the control of circulation of documents, a systematic physical inspection of the goods and the mutual exchange of information on import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the state of Value Added Tax and excise duty</seg>
<seg id="55">Value Added Tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (hereinafter "VAT") was levied by the financial or tax authorities of the taxable transactions carried out in the territory of the country and the customs authorities upon importation of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">Tax revenues were due to the difference between the tax liability collected and the excess VAT deductions refunded.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenues at customs offices were determined by the amount of tax collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">Tax collected by customs authorities, in accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, was reflected in the tax deductions applied to financial or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most financial and tax authorities, excess deductions exceeded the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">The VAT is in terms of revenue of the state budget one of the flagship tax, since the tax revenues of the state budget of the CZECH republic in 2003, contributed about 31 % and the tax revenue of the state budget of the SR to approximately 42%.</seg>
<seg id="62">The total VAT collection in the Czech Republic was CZK 162.9 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="63">The financial and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 394.3 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions returned were CZK 231.4 billion in total.</seg>
<seg id="64">The total VAT collection in SR amounted to SKK 83.8 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="65">In 2003, the tax and customs authorities levied CZK 187.0 billion in VAT and the excess VAT deductions refunded amounted to CZK 103.2 billion.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise duties</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as "SpD") was carried out by the relevant financial and / or tax authorities and on importation of products subject to SpD by customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The SpD's share of the tax revenues of the state budget in the Czech Republic was approximately 16% in 2003 and about 19% in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="69">Total collection of SpD selected in the CZECH republic, financial and customs authorities in the year 2003 amounted to 85,6 billion and SR achieve the above 38,0 billion Sk.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. Course of control action</seg>
<seg id="71">Cooperation between the SAO and the Sao SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, a comparison was made between the imports and exports of selected commodities from customs databases in the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA, in the second stage were the results of this comparison used in the mutual verification of the implementation of selected business transactions between the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA and during the checks carried out on the territory of both states.</seg>
