<seg id="2">Joint report on the parallel audit by the Czech Supreme audit office (SAO) and the German Federal court of auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and the private sphere.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the state is to use public resources as effectively and efficiently and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor in the success of the Single Economic Area.</seg>
<seg id="7">The EU in its legislation has set limits above which the ca must meet certain requirements to guarantee the wide and limitless competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU member states must therefore transpose the European tender right into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">Both the Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts that are below EU limits, the regulation of their procurement remains within the competence of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In addition, public procurement is vulnerable to corruption with a consequent high potential for damage.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting entities are obliged to adopt in their procurement procedures reasonable measures to prevent corruption and improper favoritism (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011 the Supreme audit office of the Czech republic (Czech SAI – SAO) and the Federal accounting court of Germany (the German SAI – BRH) agree to perform parallel inspections in the field of procurement management and prevention of corruption in land and road construction.</seg>
