<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in excise control checks between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">Presented to the joint report informs of the progress and outcome of international cooperation in the parallel controls, which implement the Supreme audit office, Czech republic Najvyšší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky, focused on the administration of excise taxes in the period after the entry of both countries into the European union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement in control activities concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The theme of the parallel controls were selected with respect to a fundamental change in the system of collection of excise taxes that occurred in connection with the inclusion of the Czech republic and the Slovak republic into the internal market of the European union from 1. May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the internal market of the European Union requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow the circulation of goods unburdened by tax up to the date of delivery for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with this principle, the new legislation adopted in both countries allows the movement of goods under tax supervision under the conditional exemption regime.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great demands on tax authorities and presupposes a close interaction between the competent administrations of the member states in the fight against tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in excise control checks for the period from 1. May 2004 to 31. December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (ČR) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of inspection: (CR) Excise Tax Administration (SR) procedure of cobrné bodies in the management of consumption taxes</seg>
<seg id="14">The supreme audit office, Czech republic (hereinafter the "NKU-CZ") and the Najvyšší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky (hereinafter referred to as "SAO SR") has concluded on the 8th. February 2006 "contract of cooperation in control activities".</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel checks carried out "Excise Management", included in the Sao-CR's 2005 audit plan under no 05/34, and "control of the Cobra procedure in the management of consumption taxes", included in the Sao SR's 2006 audit plan under no 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel controls had the character of a coordinated control.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information, which the contracting parties could not get in control of the administration of excise taxes on the territory of its state, and in the development of a common final report on the results of the checks within the meaning of the european implementing guidelines for implementation of the audit standards INTOSAI - directive no 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">On the territory of the Czech republic's control (hereinafter referred to as "CR") implement the group controlling department of the state budget and from territorial departments of the central Bohemia, south bohemia, west Bohemia, north-west Bohemia north-east Bohemia, south Moravia, central Moravia and north Moravia in the period from 7. February to 2. June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">27 inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="20">The audited persons were the Directorate-General of Customs (hereinafter referred to as DGC) and 11 tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the DG, 12 selected customs offices were inspected out of a total of 54.</seg>
<seg id="22">Control on the territory of the Slovak republic (hereinafter "SR") conducted by the section of financial and tax the SAO SR, in cooperation with the expoziturami the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice on the 5 customs offices from a total of 9 in the period from 13. February to 2. June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">8 inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of the parallel checks was to examine the customs procedure for the administration of excise duties and compliance with the relevant legislation in force in both countries and the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">The international cooperation was focused on the procedure of the administrators of taxes in the exercise of supervision of the transport of the goods subject to consumption taxes, in particular on the registration of launched and completed transport in the regime of conditional exemption from tax, and the exchange of information within the framework of mutual administrative assistance between the administrators of the excise taxes the CZECH republic and SLOVAKIA.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Excise tax administration</seg>
<seg id="27">Excise duties were administered in the Czech Republic until 31. December 2003 financial authorities.</seg>
<seg id="28">From 1. in January 2004, this agenda was taken over by the customs authorities, which have so far levied excise duty only on imports.</seg>
<seg id="29">Excise duty is subject to mineral oils, alcohol, beer, wine and intermediate products and tobacco products in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="30">The income of the state budget from excise taxes in the Czech Republic was CZK 82.8 billion in 2004 and the revenue of the state budget from taxes and fees of CZK 424.7 billion was 19.5 %.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005, the income of the state budget from excise taxes 103,6 billion Czk and the share on the revenue of the state budget from taxes and fees in the amount of $ 460.4 billion Czk was of 22.5 %.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the revenue from excise duty on mineral oils to the state budget 80% of the total revenue from this tax, and in 2005 accounted for 90.9 %.</seg>
<seg id="33">The difference against 100% of CZK 13 billion in 2004 and CZK 6.9 billion in 2005 was the income of the state fund for transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="34">The administration of all excise duties in the SR shall be carried out by the customs authorities from 1. May 2004, with the exception of the excise duty on mineral oil which they have been administering since 1. 1, 2002.</seg>
<seg id="35">Until then, the excise administration was carried out by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="36">Excise duty in SR is subject to mineral oil, alcohol, beer, wine and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="37">The state budget's revenue from excise duties in the SR was a total of Sk 43.4 billion in 2004 and the total tax revenue of Sk 209.5 billion was 20.7 %.</seg>
<seg id="38">In 2005, the state budget revenue from excise taxes was Sk. 50 billion, and in total tax revenues of Sk. 222.6 billion, excise taxes accounted for 22.5 %.</seg>
<seg id="39">Chart No. 1-Comparison of revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic from taxes and fees and tax revenues of the state budget of the SR with excise income</seg>
<seg id="40">The legislation in both countries is based on European union regulations governing this area, in particular: - Council directive 92/12/EEC on the general arrangements, holding, movement and monitoring of products subject to excise duty (hereinafter "the directive 92/12/EEC"), - Council regulation (EC) no 2073/2004 on administrative cooperation in the field of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as "regulation no 2073/2004"), - Commission regulation (EEC) no 2719/92 on the accompanying administrative document for the movement of excisable products under a duty suspension arrangement from the excise tax (hereinafter referred to as "regulation no 2719/92"), - Commission regulation (EEC) no 3649/92 on a simplified accompanying document for the movement of products subject to excise duty which have been released for consumption in the member state of dispatch, within the Community (hereinafter "regulation no 3649/92").</seg>
<seg id="41">The basic legislation regulating excise duties in the Czech Republic is Act No. 353/2003 Coll. on excise duties, as amended ,( hereinafter referred to as " Act no 353/2003 Coll.“ ) effective from 1. January 2004.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the administration of excise duties in the SR, the customs authorities are bound, inter alia, by the following generally binding legislation: - law no 98/2004 Z. z. about the consumption tax on mineral oil in the neskorí predpisov act (hereinafter referred to as " law no 98/2004 Z. z."),- law no 104/2004 Z. z. on the consumption tax on wine in the name of neskorí predpisov (hereinafter referred to as "law no 104/2004 Z. z."),- law no 105/2004 Z. z. on the consumption tax of Lieh in the neskorí predpisov act (hereinafter referred to as "law no 105/2004 Z. z."),- law no 106/2004 Z. z. on the consumption tax on Tabak products in the name of neskorší predpisov (hereinafter referred to as "law no 106/2004 Z. z."),- law no 107/2004 Z. z. about the consumption tax on beer in the neskorší predpisov act (hereinafter referred to as "law no 107/2004 Z. z.“).</seg>
<seg id="43">2.1. movement of excise goods under a conditional exemption scheme between member states of the European Union</seg>
