<seg id="604">4.5.4 comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">Differences in the responses of both the member states show that the Czech republic provides a system that collects the amount of data of the carried-out tax inspections and further data from the statements of the accounts - the balance sheet and statements of profit and loss.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to regulate the selection of cases with a risk-prone nature.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the analysis and management of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, the establishment of a specialized tax office for the administration of VDS is planned in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax administration does not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">It follows from this that it is more difficult to carry out these tasks in a similar way.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, Germany's philosophy places more emphasis on the selection of individual cases on the basis of data from the tax returns submitted.</seg>
<seg id="612">The risk management components will therefore be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of adequate reference notes, expert auditors must be able to measure the exact amount of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="614">Both SAI concur in the opinion that member states should be able to ensure adequate financial management and adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help reduce outages in VAT revenue.</seg>
<seg id="616">As a result, the return on VAT collection will increase and the level of risk detection among unreliable entrepreneurs will improve.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">Cooperation between the two SAI on parallel controls of VAT management has met the objectives set by the SAO and the BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">Both SAI know each other better applicable systems in the following areas: • intracommunity transactions, • risk management, VAT, in particular as regards the choice of transaction is prone to risk, • assistance in recovery of VAT and • control of VAT for large taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to mutual cooperation, differences in VAT fraud detection strategies and differences in the above VAT management areas in the Czech Republic and Germany were revealed.</seg>
<seg id="621">The control findings were compared and best practices were identified on their basis.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, both SAI hope that the results achieved will provide an impetus for stakeholders to start discussing approaches and strategies within the member states, among them at European Commission level.</seg>
<seg id="623">The extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation of both SAI can serve as an encouragement for the implementation of future VAT management control actions.</seg>
